															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-reach" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1779895); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1779895&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204210" alt="Dr Reach" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1779895)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-reach" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1779895); return false;" >Dr Reach</a></span> <span class="odate time_1425694631 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Mar 2015 02:17</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2246298">
									

<p>I'm&#8230; not convinced.</p>
<p>Indeed, it's an attractive re-imagining. But the whole story feels kinda mashed together at some points, and deserving of a more in-depth exploration of the universe where it exists. Is this an Unfounded-compatible tale? Is this an incarnation of the Foundation posing as the Church of the Broken God (and thus making a horribad job of actual containment)? Is this a corrupt Church altogether?</p>
<p>The messianic concept also drips a bit too much of a messiah according to the Christian archetype. A human mother that is impregnated through divine act and will, thus gives birth to a little bundle of reality-defying skills who grows up to die fighting a traitorous enemy and then is brought back by a mourning father; true, it might be Qabil playing history to his benefit, but it makes me feel a bit too detracted from the story. It's a story I've read before, after all.</p>
<p>Otherwise, the writing feels solid to me, and the Conspectus format remains the best goi_format in this site; you could have played a bit more with the footnotes, but all in all, it's a good doc. I'm torn. I'll come back before the voting period is over, but for now, no-vote.</p>

							</div>

								
					
